"# Chapter 16: The Crescendo — the Beat Machine

You've built a tone from sine waves, shaped it with envelopes, colored it with filters and formants, wrapped it in an instrument, and sequenced it in time. You've decomposed sound back into spectrum, transcribed melodies, and even made surfaces react to touch. Now we climb the last hill: **the machine that writes the route for you**.

The beat machine is a pad where you *play* a rhythm by hand—tap the kick, snare, hi-hat, clap—and the machine watches what you built and **emits the Motoi Scheme for your beat**. Not a MIDI file, not a binary blob—*code*. The pattern you invented becomes a route you can read, edit, save, remix, and fold into bigger compositions. The machine composes for you, and you teach the machine by playing.

This is the crescendo. Everything we drilled was for this: the waveform so you know what you're placing, the envelope so the kick punches and the hi-hat rings, the timing transport so the machine can schedule what you played, the sequencer idioms so the emitted code is clean. We'll start with a simple one-shot trigger, then a four-step loop, then a full sixteen-step kit with swing and accents, and finally the machine that writes the pattern back as a `(define ...)` form you can paste and run.

## One-Shot Triggers — The Simplest Beat Machine

A beat machine at its core is a **trigger grid**: tap a pad, emit the sound *and* the code that made it.

```scheme
;; tap the kick — play it AND print the route that triggered it
(define (trigger-kick)
  (let ((sound (tone 60 0.3)))
    (display \"(tone 60 0.3)\\n\")
    sound))

(trigger-kick)
```

[VISUAL: A single pad labeled \"KICK\" — tap it, hear the thump, see the code `(tone 60 0.3)` print below.]

The machine doesn't just play the sound; it *remembers* what it did and tells you how to do it again. That's the trick. Every action is logged as the code that produced it.

```scheme
;; three pads: kick, snare, hat
(define (trigger-snare)
  (let ((sound (add-formant (noise 'white) '(200 800))))
    (display \"(add-formant (noise 'white) '(200 800))\\n\")
    sound))

(define (trigger-hat)
  (let ((sound (filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 8000 :q 2)))
    (display \"(filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 8000 :q 2)\\n\")
    sound))

(define (trigger-kick)
  (display \"(tone 60 0.3)\\n\")
  (tone 60 0.3))

;; tap each pad in turn
(trigger-kick)
(trigger-snare)
(trigger-hat)
```

*[needs: filter :cutoff]*  
<!-- BUILD: filter verb with :cutoff + :q keyword params -->

Three pads, three sounds, three lines of code printed. The console becomes a *transcript* of what you played.

## Recording a Sequence — Timestamped Triggers

When you tap, *when* matters as much as *what*. A beat machine needs to remember the *time* of each hit.

```scheme
;; record a sequence of triggers with timestamps (in beats)
(define beat-log '())

(define (tap-kick beat)
  (set! beat-log (cons (list beat 'kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\") beat-log))
  (tone 60 0.3))

(define (tap-snare beat)
  (set! beat-log (cons (list beat 'snare \"(noise 'white)\") beat-log))
  (noise 'white))

;; tap the kick at beat 0, snare at beat 1
(tap-kick 0)
(tap-snare 1)

;; show the log
(display beat-log)
;; => ((1 snare \"(noise 'white)\") (0 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\"))
```

The log is a list of `(beat instrument code)` tuples. We can replay it, edit it, quantize it, or emit it as a `schedule` route.

## Emitting a Schedule Route

Now we transform the log into a runnable `(schedule ...)` form.

```scheme
;; convert the log to a schedule route
(define beat-log
  '((0 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (1 snare \"(noise 'white)\")
    (2 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (3 hat \"(noise 'pink)\")))

(define (emit-schedule log)
  (display \"(schedule\\n\")
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (let ((beat (car entry))
            (code (caddr entry)))
        (display \"  (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display code)
        (display \")\\n\")))
    log)
  (display \")\\n\"))

(emit-schedule beat-log)
;; prints:
;; (schedule
;;   (:at 0 (tone 60 0.3))
;;   (:at 1 (noise 'white))
;;   (:at 2 (tone 60 0.3))
;;   (:at 3 (noise 'pink))
;; )
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*  
<!-- BUILD: schedule verb with :at keyword for beat placement -->

The emitted code is a **score**. You can copy it, tweak the beats, change the tones, and run it.

## Quantizing the Log — Snap to Grid

Human taps are messy. A beat machine can snap them to the nearest eighth or sixteenth.

```scheme
;; quantize a beat to the nearest grid step
(define (quantize-beat beat grid)
  (* grid (round (/ beat grid))))

;; you tapped at beat 0.8 — snap to the nearest half-beat
(quantize-beat 0.8 0.5)
;; => 1.0

;; you tapped at beat 2.3 — snap to the nearest quarter
(quantize-beat 2.3 0.25)
;; => 2.25
```

```scheme
;; quantize the entire log
(define raw-log
  '((0.2 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (0.9 snare \"(noise 'white)\")
    (1.8 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (2.7 hat \"(noise 'pink)\")))

(define (quantize-log log grid)
  (map
    (lambda (entry)
      (list (quantize-beat (car entry) grid)
            (cadr entry)
            (caddr entry)))
    log))

(quantize-log raw-log 0.5)
;; => ((0.0 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
;;     (1.0 snare \"(noise 'white)\")
;;     (2.0 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
;;     (3.0 hat \"(noise 'pink)\"))
```

Sloppy taps become a clean grid. The machine forgives your timing.

## Four-Step Loop — The Classic Drum Machine

A step sequencer is a *spatial* interface: sixteen squares, one per sixteenth note. Tap a square to toggle it on; the loop plays forever.

```scheme
;; a four-step kick pattern: on-off-on-off
(define kick-pattern '(#t #f #t #f))

(define (play-pattern pattern sound beats-per-step)
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (display \"(schedule (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display sound)
        (display \"))\\n\"))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat beats-per-step)))))

(play-pattern kick-pattern \"(tone 60 0.3)\" 0.25)
;; prints:
;; (schedule (:at 0 (tone 60 0.3)))
;; (schedule (:at 0.5 (tone 60 0.3)))
```

A pattern is a boolean list. `#t` means \"trigger here,\" `#f` means \"rest.\" The machine walks the list, printing a `schedule` line for every `#t`.

## Multi-Track Patterns — Kick + Snare + Hat

A real drum machine has many rows.

```scheme
;; three tracks: kick, snare, hat
(define kick-pattern  '(#t #f #t #f))
(define snare-pattern '(#f #t #f #t))
(define hat-pattern   '(#t #t #t #t))

(define (emit-track name pattern sound step-dur)
  (display (string-append \";; \" name \"\\n\"))
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (display \"(schedule (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display sound)
        (display \"))\\n\"))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(emit-track \"kick\" kick-pattern \"(tone 60 0.3)\" 0.25)
(emit-track \"snare\" snare-pattern \"(noise 'white)\" 0.25)
(emit-track \"hat\" hat-pattern \"(filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 8000)\" 0.25)
```

*[needs: filter :cutoff]*

Three tracks, three patterns, one unified schedule. The emitted code interleaves them.

## Sixteen-Step Grid — The Full Machine

Now we scale to sixteen steps—the classic 808/909 layout.

```scheme
;; sixteen-step kick: four-on-the-floor
(define kick-16 '(#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))

;; sixteen-step snare: backbeat on 4 and 12
(define snare-16 '(#f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f  #f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f))

;; sixteen-step hat: steady eighths
(define hat-16 '(#t #f #t #f  #t #f #t #f  #t #f #t #f  #t #f #t #f))

(define (emit-pattern-schedule tracks step-dur)
  (for-each
    (lambda (track)
      (let ((name (car track))
            (pattern (cadr track))
            (sound (caddr track)))
        (display (string-append \"\\n;; \" name \"\\n\"))
        (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
          (when (not (null? steps))
            (when (car steps)
              (display \"(schedule (:at \")
              (display beat)
              (display \" \")
              (display sound)
              (display \"))\\n\"))
            (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))
    tracks))

(emit-pattern-schedule
  (list
    (list \"kick\" kick-16 \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (list \"snare\" snare-16 \"(noise 'white)\")
    (list \"hat\" hat-16 \"(filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 8000)\"))
  0.25)
```

*[needs: filter :cutoff]*

A classic house beat: kick on every quarter, snare on the two and four, hi-hat on the eighths. The machine emits the full schedule.

[VISUAL: A 16×3 grid — three rows (kick/snare/hat), sixteen columns (one per sixteenth). Lit squares are triggers. Below the grid, the emitted schedule scrolls as code.]

## Accent and Velocity — Not All Hits Are Equal

A 909 has *accent*—some hits louder than others. We can encode that as amplitude.

```scheme
;; a pattern with amplitude: (step-on? amplitude)
(define kick-accented
  '((#t 1.0) (#f 0.0) (#t 0.6) (#f 0.0)
    (#t 1.0) (#f 0.0) (#t 0.6) (#f 0.0)))

(define (emit-accented-pattern pattern sound step-dur)
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (let ((on? (caar steps))
            (amp (cadar steps)))
        (when on?
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" (* \")
          (display amp)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \")))\\n\")))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(emit-accented-pattern kick-accented \"(tone 60 0.3)\" 0.25)
;; prints:
;; (schedule (:at 0 (* 1.0 (tone 60 0.3))))
;; (schedule (:at 0.5 (* 0.6 (tone 60 0.3))))
;; (schedule (:at 1.0 (* 1.0 (tone 60 0.3))))
;; ...
```

The first and fifth kicks are full-strength; the third and seventh are ghost notes. The code multiplies the tone by the accent level.

## Swing — Delaying Every Other Step

Swing shifts the offbeat eighth notes later in time—16th-note triplet swing is the classic feel.

```scheme
;; apply swing: delay every odd-indexed step by a fraction
(define (apply-swing beat step-index swing-amount)
  (if (odd? step-index)
      (+ beat (* swing-amount 0.125))  ;; delay by fraction of a sixteenth
      beat))

;; a straight hat pattern
(define hat-straight '(#t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t))

(define (emit-swung-pattern pattern sound step-dur swing)
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (index 0) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (let ((swung-beat (apply-swing beat index swing)))
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display swung-beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\")))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ index 1) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(emit-swung-pattern hat-straight \"(noise 'pink)\" 0.25 0.5)
;; every odd step delayed by 1/16 of a beat
```

Straight time becomes shuffle. The emitted timestamps are no longer on the grid.

## Kit Assignment — Map Pads to Sounds

A beat machine is a *kit*: a collection of sounds bound to pads.

```scheme
;; define a kit: pad -> sound code
(define kit-808
  '((kick . \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (snare . \"(add-formant (noise 'white) '(200 800))\")
    (hat . \"(filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 8000)\")
    (clap . \"(noise 'pink)\")))

(define (get-sound kit pad)
  (cdr (assoc pad kit)))

(get-sound kit-808 'kick)
;; => \"(tone 60 0.3)\"

(get-sound kit-808 'clap)
;; => \"(noise 'pink)\"
```

The kit is an association list. You can swap kits to change the character of the beat.

```scheme
;; a different kit: 909-style
(define kit-909
  '((kick . \"(tone 55 0.4)\")
    (snare . \"(add-formant (noise 'white) '(180 900))\")
    (hat . \"(filter 'highpass (noise 'white) :cutoff 9000)\")
    (clap . \"(add-formant (noise 'white) '(1000 2500))\")))

(define (emit-pattern-with-kit pattern kit pad step-dur)
  (let ((sound (get-sound kit pad)))
    (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-pattern-with-kit '(#t #f #t #f) kit-909 'kick 0.25)
```

*[needs: filter :cutoff, add-formant]*  
<!-- BUILD: add-formant verb for resonance peaks -->

Same pattern, different kit—different sound. The code changes but the rhythm doesn't.

## Named Patterns — Define and Reuse

A beat machine should let you *name* a pattern so you can recall and combine it.

```scheme
;; define a library of named patterns
(define pattern-lib
  '((four-floor . (#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))
    (backbeat . (#f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f  #f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f))
    (steady-hats . (#t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t))
    (offbeat-hats . (#f #t #f #t  #f #t #f #t  #f #t #f #t  #f #t #f #t))))

(define (get-pattern lib name)
  (cdr (assoc name lib)))

(get-pattern pattern-lib 'four-floor)
;; => (#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f)
```

Now you can compose beats by *name*:

```scheme
(define (emit-named-beat kit patterns step-dur)
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (let ((pad (car entry))
            (pattern-name (cadr entry)))
        (let ((pattern (get-pattern pattern-lib pattern-name))
              (sound (get-sound kit pad)))
          (display (string-append \"\\n;; \" (symbol->string pad) 
                                  \" — \" (symbol->string pattern-name) \"\\n\"))
          (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
            (when (not (null? steps))
              (when (car steps)
                (display \"(schedule (:at \")
                (display beat)
                (display \" \")
                (display sound)
                (display \"))\\n\"))
              (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))))
    patterns))

(emit-named-beat kit-808
  '((kick four-floor)
    (snare backbeat)
    (hat steady-hats))
  0.25)
```

*[needs: filter :cutoff, add-formant]*

The beat is now a *composition* of named patterns and a chosen kit. The code is modular.

## Euclidean Rhythms — Distribute N Hits Over M Steps

Euclidean rhythms are the even-as-possible distribution of onsets—ancient bell patterns, clave, tresillo.

```scheme
;; euclidean rhythm: distribute k hits over n steps
(define (euclidean k n)
  (let ((pattern (make-list n #f)))
    (let loop ((i 0) (hits k) (acc pattern))
      (if (>= i n)
          acc
          (let* ((step-val (>= (* hits n) (* k i)))
                 (new-hits (if step-val (- hits 1) hits)))
            (loop (+ i 1) new-hits
                  (append (take acc i)
                          (list step-val)
                          (drop acc (+ i 1)))))))))

;; 5 hits in 8 steps
(euclidean 5 8)
;; => (#t #f #t #t #f #t #t #f)  ;; close to a clave
```

```scheme
;; helper: take and drop
(define (take lst n)
  (if (or (= n 0) (null? lst))
      '()
      (cons (car lst) (take (cdr lst) (- n 1)))))

(define (drop lst n)
  (if (or (= n 0) (null? lst))
      lst
      (drop (cdr lst) (- n 1))))

(define (make-list n val)
  (if (= n 0)
      '()
      (cons val (make-list (- n 1) val))))

(define (euclidean k n)
  (let loop ((i 0) (pattern '()))
    (if (>= i n)
        (reverse pattern)
        (loop (+ i 1)
              (cons (< (* i k) (* (+ i 1) k (/ 1 n))) pattern)))))

;; 3 hits in 8 steps
(euclidean 3 8)
;; => (#t #f #f #t #f #f #t #f)  ;; tresillo
```

The emitted pattern is mathematically even. You can emit it just like any other:

```scheme
(define (emit-euclidean k n sound step-dur)
  (let ((pattern (euclidean k n)))
    (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-euclidean 5 16 \"(tone 60 0.2)\" 0.25)
```

A rhythm from an algorithm, emitted as code.

## Pattern Rotation — Shift the Downbeat

Rotating a pattern changes where it starts—same hits, different groove.

```scheme
;; rotate a list left by n steps
(define (rotate lst n)
  (if (or (null? lst) (<= n 0))
      lst
      (rotate (append (cdr lst) (list (car lst))) (- n 1))))

(define pat '(#t #f #t #f  #t #f #f #f))

(rotate pat 0)
;; => (#t #f #t #f  #t #f #f #f)

(rotate pat 2)
;; => (#t #f #t #f  #f #f #t #f)
```

```scheme
;; emit a rotated pattern
(define (emit-rotated pattern rotation sound step-dur)
  (let ((rotated (rotate pattern rotation)))
    (let loop ((steps rotated) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-rotated '(#t #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f) 3 \"(tone 60 0.2)\" 0.25)
```

Same hits, new pocket. The machine can rotate patterns on the fly.

## Layering Patterns — Combine Two into One

Sometimes you want to *merge* two patterns—play both at once.

```scheme
;; OR two patterns together
(define (layer-patterns p1 p2)
  (map (lambda (a b) (or a b)) p1 p2))

(define pat-a '(#t #f #t #f))
(define pat-b '(#f #t #f #f))

(layer-patterns pat-a pat-b)
;; => (#t #t #t #f)
```

```scheme
;; emit a layered pattern
(define (emit-layered p1 p2 sound step-dur)
  (let ((merged (layer-patterns p1 p2)))
    (let loop ((steps merged) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-layered '(#t #f #f #f) '(#f #f #t #f) \"(tone 60 0.2)\" 0.25)
```

Two rhythms become one. The machine can compose patterns algorithmically.

## Fill Detection — Recognize a Roll

A fill is a dense run of hits—more than N triggers in a row.

```scheme
;; detect a fill: count consecutive #t
(define (count-consecutive-true lst)
  (let loop ((l lst) (count 0) (max-count 0))
    (cond
      ((null? l) max-count)
      ((car l) (loop (cdr l) (+ count 1) (max (+ count 1) max-count)))
      (else (loop (cdr l) 0 max-count)))))

(count-consecutive-true '(#f #t #t #t #f #f))
;; => 3

(count-consecutive-true '(#t #t #t #t #t))
;; => 5
```

```scheme
;; is this a fill? (four or more hits in a row)
(define (is-fill? pattern)
  (>= (count-consecutive-true pattern) 4))

(is-fill? '(#f #t #t #t #t #f))
;; => #t

(is-fill? '(#f #t #f #t #f #t))
;; => #f
```

The machine can *detect* that you played a fill and emit a comment or tag.

```scheme
(define (emit-with-fill-tag pattern sound step-dur)
  (when (is-fill? pattern)
    (display \";; FILL DETECTED\\n\"))
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (display \"(schedule (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display sound)
        (display \"))\\n\"))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(emit-with-fill-tag '(#t #t #t #t) \"(tone 60 0.1)\" 0.25)
;; prints:
;; ;; FILL DETECTED
;; (schedule (:at 0 (tone 60 0.1)))
;; ...
```

The emitted code is annotated. The machine is listening.

## Pattern Compression — Represent Runs

Instead of `(#t #t #t #t #f #f)`, we can write `((4 . #t) (2 . #f))`—run-length encoding.

```scheme
;; run-length encode a pattern
(define (rle pattern)
  (if (null? pattern)
      '()
      (let loop ((rest (cdr pattern)) (current (car pattern)) (count 1) (acc '()))
        (cond
          ((null? rest)
           (reverse (cons (cons count current) acc)))
          ((equal? (car rest) current)
           (loop (cdr rest) current (+ count 1) acc))
          (else
           (loop (cdr rest) (car rest) 1 (cons (cons count current) acc)))))))

(rle '(#t #t #t #f #f #t))
;; => ((3 . #t) (2 . #f) (1 . #t))
```

```scheme
;; decode run-length encoding
(define (rle-decode encoded)
  (if (null? encoded)
      '()
      (let ((run (car encoded)))
        (append (make-list (car run) (cdr run))
                (rle-decode (cdr encoded))))))

(rle-decode '((3 . #t) (2 . #f) (1 . #t)))
;; => (#t #t #t #f #f #t)
```

Compression doesn't change the sound, but it makes the pattern storage smaller.

## Emitting a Pattern Library — Save the Whole Beat

Now we emit not just one pattern, but a *define* form for the whole library.

```scheme
;; emit a pattern library as a define form
(define (emit-pattern-lib lib)
  (display \"(define pattern-lib\\n  '(\")
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (display \"\\n    (\")
      (display (car entry))
      (display \" . \")
      (display (cdr entry))
      (display \")\"))
    lib)
  (display \"))\\n\"))

(emit-pattern-lib
  '((kick . (#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))
    (snare . (#f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f))
    (hat . (#t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t))))
;; prints:
;; (define pattern-lib
;;   '(
;;     (kick . (#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))
;;     (snare . (#f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f))
;;     (hat . (#t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t))))
```

The machine writes a `(define ...)` you can paste into a new file.

## Emitting a Full Beat Route — The Crescendo

Here's the payoff: emit a *complete* route—tempo, kit, patterns, schedule—ready to run.

```scheme
;; emit a full beat route
(define (emit-beat-route tempo kit patterns step-dur)
  (display \";; Beat Machine Output\\n\\n\")
  (display \"(tempo \")
  (display tempo)
  (display \")\\n\\n\")
  
  (display \"(define kit\\n  '(\")
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (display \"\\n    (\")
      (display (car entry))
      (display \" . \")
      (display (cdr entry))
      (display \")\"))
    kit)
  (display \"))\\n\\n\")
  
  (display \"(schedule\\n\")
  (for-each
    (lambda (track)
      (let ((pad (car track))
            (pattern (cadr track)))
        (let ((sound (cdr (assoc pad kit))))
          (display (string-append \"  ;; \" (symbol->string pad) \"\\n\"))
          (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
            (when (not (null? steps))
              (when (car steps)
                (display \"  (:at \")
                (display beat)
                (display \" \")
                (display sound)
                (display \")\\n\"))
              (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))))
    patterns)
  (display \")\\n\"))

(emit-beat-route
  120
  '((kick . \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (snare . \"(noise 'white)\")
    (hat . \"(noise 'pink)\"))
  '((kick . (#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))
    (snare . (#f #f #f #t  #f #f #f #f))
    (hat . (#t #t #t #t  #t #t #t #t)))
  0.25)
;; prints a complete route: (tempo 120), (define kit ...), (schedule ...)
```

*[needs: tempo, schedule :at]*

[VISUAL: A pad grid showing the active beat—kick/snare/hat rows, eight columns lit. Below, a scrolling code pane displaying the full emitted route.]

This is the crescendo. You played a beat by tapping pads. The machine wrote the Motoi Scheme for it. You can copy that code, run it, edit it, save it, share it. The beat becomes *portable knowledge*.

## Undo and Redo — The Edit Stack

A beat machine needs undo.

```scheme
;; an edit stack: list of past states
(define edit-stack '())
(define current-pattern '(#f #f #f #f))

(define (save-state pattern)
  (set! edit-stack (cons current-pattern edit-stack))
  (set! current-pattern pattern))

(define (undo)
  (if (null? edit-stack)
      (display \"Nothing to undo\\n\")
      (begin
        (set! current-pattern (car edit-stack))
        (set! edit-stack (cdr edit-stack)))))

;; edit: toggle step 2
(save-state '(#t #f #f #f))
(save-state '(#t #f #t #f))

current-pattern
;; => (#t #f #t #f)

(undo)
current-pattern
;; => (#t #f #f #f)

(undo)
current-pattern
;; => (#f #f #f #f)
```

Every edit is a checkpoint. The machine remembers what you did.

## Real-Time Playback — Emit *and* Trigger

The emitted code is a transcript, but the machine should also *play* the beat as you build it.

```scheme
;; emit AND play — pass the pitch as data, not code text.
;; note/place-at schedules the sound at a wall-clock offset so
;; every hit lands on-grid even if the loop takes a moment to run.
(define (trigger-and-emit pattern pitch step-dur)
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        ;; emit the code
        (display \"(note/place-at '\")
        (display pitch)
        (display \" \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display step-dur)
        (display \")\\n\")
        ;; and actually play it, on-grid
        (note/place-at pitch beat step-dur))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(trigger-and-emit '(#t #f #t #f) 'C4 0.25)
```

The pattern is what the beat machine composes; the emitted `note/place-at` line is what a user could paste back into a fresh session to replay it. Passing the pitch as a symbol (rather than parsing text at runtime) keeps the composition data-first — no reader-of-strings needed.

The machine prints the code *and* queues the sound. You hear what you're writing.

## Tempo Mapping — Convert Seconds to Beats

The user taps in real time (seconds), but the beat machine thinks in beats.

```scheme
;; convert seconds to beats given a tempo
(define (seconds->beats seconds bpm)
  (* seconds (/ bpm 60)))

;; you tapped at 0.5 seconds, tempo is 120
(seconds->beats 0.5 120)
;; => 1.0 beat

;; you tapped at 1.0 seconds, tempo is 90
(seconds->beats 1.0 90)
;; => 1.5 beats
```

```scheme
;; convert a time-stamped log from seconds to beats
(define (log-to-beats log bpm)
  (map
    (lambda (entry)
      (list (seconds->beats (car entry) bpm)
            (cadr entry)
            (caddr entry)))
    log))

(log-to-beats
  '((0.5 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (1.0 snare \"(noise 'white)\")
    (1.5 hat \"(noise 'pink)\"))
  120)
;; => ((1.0 kick \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
;;     (2.0 snare \"(noise 'white)\")
;;     (3.0 hat \"(noise 'pink)\"))
```

The machine translates human time into musical time.

## Pattern Mutation — Randomize a Step

A beat machine can *suggest* variations.

```scheme
;; flip a random step
(define (mutate-pattern pattern)
  (let ((index (random (length pattern))))
    (let loop ((i 0) (p pattern) (acc '()))
      (if (null? p)
          (reverse acc)
          (loop (+ i 1)
                (cdr p)
                (cons (if (= i index) (not (car p)) (car p)) acc))))))

;; requires: random, length
(define (random n) (modulo (current-jiffy) n))  ;; stub
(define (length lst)
  (if (null? lst) 0 (+ 1 (length (cdr lst)))))

(mutate-pattern '(#t #f #t #f))
;; => (#t #f #f #f)  or  (#t #t #t #f)  or  (#f #f #t #f)  — varies
```

The machine can *improvise* on your beat. Hit \"mutate\" and hear a variation.

## Copy and Paste — Duplicate a Pattern

You built a good hat pattern; now copy it to the clap track.

```scheme
;; copy pattern from pad A to pad B
(define beat-state
  '((kick . (#t #f #f #f))
    (snare . (#f #f #t #f))
    (hat . (#t #t #t #t))))

(define (copy-pattern state from-pad to-pad)
  (let ((pattern (cdr (assoc from-pad state))))
    (map
      (lambda (entry)
        (if (eq? (car entry) to-pad)
            (cons to-pad pattern)
            entry))
      state)))

(copy-pattern beat-state 'hat 'snare)
;; => ((kick . (#t #f #f #f))
;;     (snare . (#t #t #t #t))
;;     (hat . (#t #t #t #t)))
```

The snare now has the same pattern as the hat. The machine supports editing operations.

## Clear Track — Erase a Row

```scheme
;; clear a track (set all steps to #f)
(define (clear-track state pad)
  (map
    (lambda (entry)
      (if (eq? (car entry) pad)
          (cons pad (make-list (length (cdr entry)) #f))
          entry))
    state))

(clear-track beat-state 'kick)
;; => ((kick . (#f #f #f #f))
;;     (snare . (#f #f #t #f))
;;     (hat . (#t #t #t #t)))
```

The kick is silent. The machine gives you a blank slate.

## Solo and Mute — Isolate Tracks

Solo means \"play only this track.\" Mute means \"play everything but this.\"

```scheme
;; solo: emit only the given pad
(define (emit-solo state pad sound step-dur)
  (let ((pattern (cdr (assoc pad state))))
    (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-solo beat-state 'hat \"(noise 'pink)\" 0.25)
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

```scheme
;; mute: emit everything except the given pad
(define (emit-mute state pad kit step-dur)
  (for-each
    (lambda (entry)
      (let ((track-pad (car entry))
            (pattern (cdr entry)))
        (when (not (eq? track-pad pad))
          (let ((sound (cdr (assoc track-pad kit))))
            (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
              (when (not (null? steps))
                (when (car steps)
                  (display \"(schedule (:at \")
                  (display beat)
                  (display \" \")
                  (display sound)
                  (display \"))\\n\"))
                (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))))
    state))

(emit-mute beat-state 'kick
  '((kick . \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (snare . \"(noise 'white)\")
    (hat . \"(noise 'pink)\"))
  0.25)
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

The machine supports mix operations.

## Pattern Inversion — Swap On and Off

Inversion flips every step.

```scheme
;; invert a pattern
(define (invert-pattern pattern)
  (map not pattern))

(invert-pattern '(#t #f #t #f))
;; => (#f #t #f #t)
```

```scheme
;; emit an inverted pattern
(define (emit-inverted pattern sound step-dur)
  (let ((inv (invert-pattern pattern)))
    (let loop ((steps inv) (beat 0))
      (when (not (null? steps))
        (when (car steps)
          (display \"(schedule (:at \")
          (display beat)
          (display \" \")
          (display sound)
          (display \"))\\n\"))
        (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))))

(emit-inverted '(#t #f #t #f) \"(tone 60 0.2)\" 0.25)
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

The offbeats become the onbeats. The machine can algorithmically vary your idea.

## Chain Patterns — A to B to C to D

A beat machine can play a *sequence* of patterns—intro, verse, chorus, fill.

```scheme
;; chain: play patterns in order, each for N bars
(define (emit-chain chain kit step-dur steps-per-bar)
  (let loop ((segments chain) (bar 0))
    (when (not (null? segments))
      (let* ((segment (car segments))
             (pad (car segment))
             (pattern-name (cadr segment))
             (bars (caddr segment))
             (pattern (get-pattern pattern-lib pattern-name))
             (sound (get-sound kit pad))
             (start-beat (* bar steps-per-bar)))
        (display (string-append \"\\n;; Bar \" (number->string bar)
                                \" — \" (symbol->string pad)
                                \" \" (symbol->string pattern-name) \"\\n\"))
        (let inner ((steps pattern) (beat start-beat))
          (when (not (null? steps))
            (when (car steps)
              (display \"(schedule (:at \")
              (display beat)
              (display \" \")
              (display sound)
              (display \"))\\n\"))
            (inner (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur))))
        (loop (cdr segments) (+ bar bars))))))

;; play kick four-floor for 2 bars, then snare backbeat for 2 bars
(emit-chain
  '((kick four-floor 2)
    (snare backbeat 2))
  kit-808
  0.25
  16)
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

The machine composes a multi-section beat. The emitted code is a timeline.

## Export as Function — Wrap the Beat

Instead of raw `schedule` calls, emit a `(define (play-beat) ...)` function.

```scheme
;; emit a beat as a named function
(define (emit-beat-function name tempo kit patterns step-dur)
  (display \"(define (\")
  (display name)
  (display \")\\n\")
  (display \"  (tempo \")
  (display tempo)
  (display \")\\n\")
  (display \"  (schedule\\n\")
  (for-each
    (lambda (track)
      (let ((pad (car track))
            (pattern (cadr track)))
        (let ((sound (cdr (assoc pad kit))))
          (display (string-append \"    ;; \" (symbol->string pad) \"\\n\"))
          (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
            (when (not (null? steps))
              (when (car steps)
                (display \"    (:at \")
                (display beat)
                (display \" \")
                (display sound)
                (display \")\\n\"))
              (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))))
    patterns)
  (display \"  ))\\n\"))

(emit-beat-function
  'my-beat
  120
  '((kick . \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (hat . \"(noise 'pink)\"))
  '((kick . (#t #f #f #f))
    (hat . (#t #t #t #t)))
  0.25)
;; prints:
;; (define (my-beat)
;;   (tempo 120)
;;   (schedule
;;     ;; kick
;;     (:at 0 (tone 60 0.3))
;;     ;; hat
;;     (:at 0 (noise 'pink))
;;     ...
;;   ))
```

*[needs: tempo, schedule :at]*

The emitted code is a *callable* beat. You can invoke it, combine it, schedule it.

## Import a Pattern — Parse User Code

The inverse: given a `schedule` form, extract the pattern.

```scheme
;; parse a simple schedule into a pattern (stub)
(define (parse-schedule-to-pattern sched step-dur grid-size)
  ;; sched is a list of (beat sound) pairs
  ;; we bucket them into steps
  (let ((pattern (make-list grid-size #f)))
    (let loop ((events sched) (p pattern))
      (if (null? events)
          p
          (let* ((event (car events))
                 (beat (car event))
                 (step (round (/ beat step-dur))))
            (if (< step grid-size)
                (loop (cdr events)
                      (append (take p step)
                              (list #t)
                              (drop p (+ step 1))))
                (loop (cdr events) p)))))))

;; example: beats at 0, 0.5, 1.0 -> steps 0, 2, 4 (if step-dur = 0.25)
(parse-schedule-to-pattern
  '((0 \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (0.5 \"(tone 60 0.3)\")
    (1.0 \"(tone 60 0.3)\"))
  0.25
  8)
;; => (#t #f #t #f #t #f #f #f)
```

The machine can *load* a beat from code. Full round-trip.

## Live Coding Assist — Autocomplete Patterns

The machine can suggest completions based on what you've typed.

```scheme
;; given a partial pattern, suggest the next step
(define (suggest-next pattern)
  ;; simple heuristic: if last two steps are (#t #f), suggest #t (repeat the motif)
  (if (< (length pattern) 2)
      #f
      (let ((last-two (take-right pattern 2)))
        (if (equal? last-two '(#t #f))
            #t
            #f))))

(define (take-right lst n)
  (reverse (take (reverse lst) n)))

(suggest-next '(#t #f #t #f))
;; => #t  (continue the on-off pattern)

(suggest-next '(#t #t #f))
;; => #f  (no strong pattern, default to #f)
```

The machine can *predict* what you might want next. It's a co-composer.

## Multi-Bar Patterns — Extend Beyond 16

A beat doesn't have to be 16 steps—go to 32, 64, or arbitrary length.

```scheme
;; emit a 32-step pattern
(define (emit-long-pattern pattern sound step-dur)
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (display \"(schedule (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display sound)
        (display \"))\\n\"))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur)))))

(define kick-32
  '(#t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f
    #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f  #t #f #f #f))

(emit-long-pattern kick-32 \"(tone 60 0.3)\" 0.25)
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

The machine scales to any length. The code is still readable.

## Human-Readable Comments — Annotate the Output

The emitted code should explain itself.

```scheme
;; emit with comments
(define (emit-annotated pattern sound step-dur)
  (display \";; Pattern length: \")
  (display (length pattern))
  (display \"\\n\")
  (display \";; Sound: \")
  (display sound)
  (display \"\\n\\n\")
  (let loop ((steps pattern) (beat 0) (index 0))
    (when (not (null? steps))
      (when (car steps)
        (display \";; Step \")
        (display index)
        (display \"\\n\")
        (display \"(schedule (:at \")
        (display beat)
        (display \" \")
        (display sound)
        (display \"))\\n\"))
      (loop (cdr steps) (+ beat step-dur) (+ index 1)))))

(emit-annotated '(#t #f #t #f) \"(tone 60 0.2)\" 0.25)
;; prints:
;; ;; Pattern length: 4
;; ;; Sound: (tone 60 0.2)
;;
;; ;; Step 0
;; (schedule (:at 0 (tone 60 0.2)))
;; ;; Step 2
;; (schedule (:at 0.5 (tone 60 0.2)))
```

*[needs: schedule :at]*

The code is self-documenting. A future reader (or future you) knows what happened.

## Save to File — Persist the Beat

The machine should write the emitted code to disk.

```scheme
;; emit to a string (stub — in real life, use open-output-file)
(define (beat-to-string tempo kit patterns step-dur)
  (let ((port (open-output-string)))
    (parameterize ((current-output-port port))
      (display \";; Auto-generated beat\\n\")
      (display \"(tempo \")
      (display tempo)
      (display \")\\n\\n\")
      ;; ... rest of emit logic ...
      )
    (get-output-string port)))

;; In a real system:
;; (call-with-output-file \"my-beat.scm\"
;;   (lambda (port)
;;     (parameterize ((current-output-port port))
;;       (emit-beat-route ...))))
```

